ğŸ§  1. What are the Features of Spring Boot?
############################################
There are many useful features of Spring Boot. Some of them are mentioned below:
âœ… Auto-configuration 
      â¡ï¸ Spring Boot automatically configures dependencies by using @EnableAutoconfiguration annotation and reduces boilerplate code.
âœ… Spring Boot Starter POM(Project Object Model) 
      â¡ï¸ These Starter POMs are pre-configured dependencies for functions like database, security, maven configuration etc.
âœ… Spring Boot CLI (Command Line Interface) 
      â¡ï¸ This command line tool is generally for managing dependencies, creating projects and running the applications.
âœ… Actuator 
      â¡ï¸ Spring Boot Actuator provides health check, metrics and monitors the endpoints of the application. 
      â¡ï¸ It also simplifies the troubleshooting management.
âœ… Embedded Servers 
      â¡ï¸ Spring Boot contains embedded servers like Tomcat and Jetty for quick application run. No need of external servers.

ğŸ§  2. Why Spring Boot over Spring?
###################################
Spring Boot simplifies the spring features for the user.

Below are some key points which spring boot offers but spring doesnâ€™t:

ğŸ”¥ Starter POM.
ğŸ”¥ Version Management.
ğŸ”¥ Auto Configuration.
ğŸ”¥ Component Scanning.
ğŸ”¥ Embedded server.
ğŸ”¥ InMemory DB.
ğŸ”¥ Actuators
 
ğŸ§  4. SB Annotations
#####################
âœ… @SpringBootApplication 
    â¡ï¸ @SpringBootApplication annotation combines @Configuration, @EnableAutoConfiguration and @ComponentScan annotations.

âœ… @AutoConfiguration
    â¡ï¸ This annotation automatically configuring beans in the class path and automatically scans the dependencies according to the application need.

âœ… @Autowired
    â¡ï¸ Spring provides annotation-based auto-wiring by providing @Autowired annotation. 
    â¡ï¸ It is used to autowire spring bean on setter methods, instance variable, and constructor. 
    â¡ï¸ When we use @Autowired annotation, the spring container auto-wires the bean by matching data-type.

âœ… @Bean
    â¡ï¸ It is a method-level annotation. 
    â¡ï¸ It is an alternative of XML <bean> tag. 
    â¡ï¸ It tells the method to produce a bean to be managed by Spring Container.

âœ… @Component
    â¡ï¸ It is a class-level annotation. It is used to mark a Java class as a bean. 
    â¡ï¸ A Java class annotated with @Component is found during the classpath. 
    â¡ï¸ The Spring Framework pick it up and configure it in the application context as a Spring Bean.

âœ… @ComponentScan
    â¡ï¸ This annotation scans the components (@Component, @Service, etc.) in the package of annotated class and its sub-packages.

âœ… @Controller
    â¡ï¸ The @Controller is a class-level annotation. It is a specialization of @Component. 
    â¡ï¸ It marks a class as a web request handler. It is often used to serve web pages. 
    â¡ï¸ By default, it returns a string that indicates which route to redirect. It is mostly used with @RequestMapping annotation.

âœ… @Configuration
    â¡ï¸ This annotation configures the beans and packages in the class path. It is a class-level annotation. 
    â¡ï¸ The class annotated with @Configuration used by Spring Containers as a source of bean definitions.

âœ… @Required
    â¡ï¸ It applies to the bean setter method. It indicates that the annotated bean must be populated at configuration time with the required property, else it throws an exception BeanInitilizationException.

âœ… @Repository
    â¡ï¸ It is a class-level annotation. The repository is a DAOs (Data Access Object) that access the database directly. 
    â¡ï¸ The repository does all the operations related to the database.

âœ… @Service
    â¡ï¸ It is also used at class level. It tells the Spring that class contains the business logic.

âœ… @EnableAutoConfiguration
    â¡ï¸ It auto-configures the bean that is present in the classpath and configures it to run the methods. 
    â¡ï¸ The use of this annotation is reduced in Spring Boot 1.2.0 release because developers provided an alternative of the annotation, 
    â¡ï¸ i.e. @SpringBootApplication.
    â¡ï¸ @SpringBootApplication: It is a combination of three annotations @EnableAutoConfiguration, @ComponentScan, and @Configuration.

Spring MVC and REST Annotations
===============================
âœ… @RequestMapping:
    â¡ï¸ It is used to map the web requests. It has many optional elements like consumes, header, method, name, params, path, produces, and value.  
    â¡ï¸ We use it with the class as well as the method.

âœ… @RequestBody:
    â¡ï¸ It is used to bind HTTP request with an object in a method parameter. Internally it uses HTTP MessageConverters to convert the body of the request.
    â¡ï¸ When we annotate a method parameter with @RequestBody, the Spring framework binds the incoming HTTP request body to that parameter.

âœ… @ResponseBody: 
    â¡ï¸ It binds the method return value to the response body. 
    â¡ï¸ It tells the Spring Boot Framework to serialize a return an object into JSON and XML format.
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            
âœ… @PathVariable: 
    â¡ï¸ It is used to extract the values from the URI. It is most suitable for the RESTful web service, where the URL contains a path variable.
    â¡ï¸ We can define multiple @PathVariable in a method.

âœ… @RequestParam: 
    â¡ï¸ It is used to extract the query parameters form the URL. It is also known as a query parameter. It is most suitable for web applications. 
    â¡ï¸ It can specify default values if the query parameter is not present in the URL.

âœ… @RequestHeader: 
    â¡ï¸ It is used to get the details about the HTTP request headers. We use this annotation as a method parameter. 
    â¡ï¸ The optional elements of the annotation are name, required, value, defaultValue. For each detail in the header, we should specify separate annotations. 
    â¡ï¸ We can use it multiple time in a method

âœ… @RestController: 
    â¡ï¸ It can be considered as a combination of @Controller and @ResponseBody annotations. 
    â¡ï¸ The @RestController annotation is itself annotated with the @ResponseBody annotation. 
    â¡ï¸ It eliminates the need for annotating each method with @ResponseBody.

âœ… @RequestAttribute: 
    â¡ï¸ It binds a method parameter to request attribute. It provides convenient access to the request attributes from a controller method. 
    â¡ï¸ With the help of @RequestAttribute annotation, we can access objects that are populated on the server-side.

